commentText: "Exploits passion": ABSOLUTELY!! Thank you for calling that out. Please listen: Blizzard, more than any other gaming company, has been selling this "dream job" experience in social media for the past decade or so. They do this because (at least in US) they underpay and overwork employees (I know this first hand at least in the engineering side). This is intentional! Be Highly skeptical of ANY company that spends that much time in social media offering things that don't matter.  THE ONLY THING THAT MATTERS when you get a job is if you are getting compensated what you are worth, and if the benefits align with your career. Everything else is bull**t. Getting paid twice as much, having a retirement plan in place before you are 30 and having enough vacation and free time daily to play/enjoy games and other entertainment.

commentText: I have worked in corporate america for over 30 years and I've witnessed a shift in business models where having a 10-year plan and meeting annual goals was the measure of success for an organization, to the quarterly earnings reports and annual revenues driving perceived health of a company. The model is all about "what have you done for me lately" rather than the traditional long-term commitment that was around when I entered the workforce. It saddens me to no end, and I honestly believe that is why poor management vexes nearly every company in the world. You cannot even call it capitalism, because that would require equal value for equal value exchanged. What we're seeing is full-out corruption, justified under the guise of "pragmatism," which couldn't be farther from the truth.   Ethics matter, and that's what was promoted when I was 18 and started my first job as a office clerk (filing, answering phones, and running errands, etc.), but that began to die in the early 1990s, with the year 2000 really pushing the new business model of expediency of the moment.

commentText: The problem with "leave when you are supposed to" is that in may places (particularly the US) people who do that, who don't voluntary work overtime out of "love for the IP" don't last long. Many nations don't have good labor laws & those that do often have a lot of loopholes. Here in Australia for example almost all hospitality jobs are casual because a company can stop giving casual staff hours without explanation of repercussion effectively firing them without actually firing them. This is heavily exploited in the club industry to get rid of guards & bar staff who do not turn a blind eye to violations of laws, etc & in countries like AUS & the US where welfare is not great people need their hours, they need their jobs so you end up with a situation where people are indirectly pressured to do things like unpaid overtime or ignoring regulations.

videoDescription: The Blizzard layoffs have hit their European HQ in Versailles, France. 134 positions are being cut out of a total of 400, with the ...
commentText: My wife worked for a company that kept claiming they needed her to work late but could not pay overtime so they would give her "comp time" after things were caught up. This ended up with her working 4-5 hours past the end of her day. She was stressed completely out, my kids were eating sandwiches for dinner because I work until midnight, and she was leaving a rather bad part of town at 10 pm. I kept asking her, then telling her, then coming just short of yelling at her that they did not give a fuck about her and she should not, could not work for free because I knew that they would claim that they could not give her the extra time off that was promised since they would not hire people to do the workload to start with. I told her over and over that they would drop her at a moments notice and not care one bit about her if they felt like it because of the labor laws in the state she worked. Sure enough, she made a very simple clerical error at 10 pm at night, off the clock, but because it reached the regional management they fired her. Not only did they fire her but the day she was fired they had her clock out at five, finish some work up from another employee that had already left at their scheduled time, then fired her at around 630 at night. She had by our records over 100 hours owed to her and never saw a minute of it in compensation. She tried to claim her unemployment benefits while looking for a new job and the manager that fired her changed the wording on her dismissal and made her not eligible for unemployment saying she was dismissed for maliciously breaking a rule. Needless to say we were quite pleased to hear that not only had that manage been fired a few months later for repeated lies to the upper management about why the office was so behind and my wife was even asked if she would testify as to the hours that she was asked to work for free but that never materialized. We also found out that many of the employees who were working just as late as her were being paid full overtime hours because they refused to work for free but were told with threat of their jobs not to mention that fact so others would not complain. Morale of the story, listen to your husband (lol I had to get that in) and companies do not give a flying fuck about you so take care of yourself.

commentText: I don't know about La Hague, but Ireland is famous in the EU for having lots of taxes and in general one of the most attractive fiscality for large companies. In fact, it is considered one of the "beachhead" for companies like the GAFAs to enter the Schengen area. The most famous example of that was that when Amazon got a large fine from the EU, Ireland went so far as to pay their fine for them to ensure they would stay in Ireland, leading to a lot of tensions with the other countries in the EU.  Otherwise, you're totally right about France. I had an interesting conversation the other day with someone from Germany who said that this massive layoff couldn't happen in a Social Economy like Germany. And indeed it could, but there's also a reason why all the great tech companies are from the US and not Germany. If Blizzard was German or French, they wouldn't have employed so many people in the first place. i think this layoff story is only possible in the US or other low workers rights countries like it. But what the employee pay with instability, they get rewarded with lots of job opportunity, as you can see the countless job proposition that followed the news. Honestly, this is sad news, but those people are way more lucky than if they would have been in France or Germany, as finding a new job would be way more difficult for them than in the US which has one of the most dynamic technology sector than any EU countries.

commentText: According to the European Constitution (the European Treaties), the second chamber must propose to the first chamber a head of government. In normal countries this is done by the Head of State.  The second chamber consists of the heads of government of the member states. They told the second chamber that they would only accept one of these people. They have justified this with "more democracy", which can be seen as such.  In 2014 it was easy because the two largest parties together had over 50%. Now in 2019 the parliament has completely blocked itself. Now the second chamber has simply done what it has to do according to the constitution. And everyone is screaming "this is undemocratic!

videoTitle: Parliament clashes with Tusk over EU top jobs

commentText:
For those of us who have studied European Law, this is not a surprise!  Yes compared to the 2014 EU parliamentary elections its a step-back to the old. But the Treaty says nothing about DIRECTLY voting the Commission (EXECUTIVE). That's why EU citizens ONLY vote for PARLIAMENT elections.   Historical Background: Actually, compared to how the European Parliament began back in 1979, as an Assembly, and not as a Parliament, indicates improvement to the structure of our Union. In essence, even the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, which formalised the 3 pillar structure and created European citizenship, held the Parliament STILL with the less control over the co-legislative procedure as well as with NO consent power over political issues, such as the one at hand, namely the consent on the selection of the Commission's president, the Commissioners and the High Representative for foreign affairs. The Member States, since the 90s, refused to provide the Parliament with more legal powers, which indicated their willingness to keep the Parliament and generally the EEC undemocratic to their own benefit. Many people in the UK do not understand this. It wasn't the EEC's fault, but the Countries' fault, especially those who were against democratising the process, such as the UK. (Brexit irony when you hear someone from the UK talking about the undemocratic process)   In contrast to the Treaties that came after Maastricht, (Amsterdam and Nice Treaties), it is the 2009 Lisbon Treaty which democratised  the European Council's powers, by requiring consent from the European Parliament. Moreover, the Parliament is now stronger more than ever, not only in legislating (together with the Council of Ministers) , but in requiring its consent (majority vote), on things such as trade agreements negotiated by the Commission and the rest of the world, or  on supervising the competence powers of executive agencies such as Frontex or the EMA or, institutions such as the ECB or even the ESM.   In other words,  for those of us who have studied the European project and EU law, we're well aware that the EU is NOW more democratic than it ever was before.    Present CASE: Now, to the issue at stake. The TEU Treaty states under Art. 17(7), 'Taking into account the elections to the European Parliament and after having held the
 appropriate consultations, the European Council, acting by a qualified majority, shall propose to
 the European Parliament a candidate for President of the Commission. This candidate shall be elected by the European Parliament by a majority of its component members. If he does not obtain the required majority, the European Council, acting by a qualified majority, shall within one month propose a new candidate who shall be elected by the European Parliament following the same procedure'.    Evidently, the States of out Union, as 'Masters of the Treaties', still keep their legal right to decide who's gonna be sitting as President of the European Commission but taking into account the political party result as well as requiring the consent/election by the European Parliament.   The MEGA question remains: Do the peoples of Europe, namely all EU citizens, wish to vote DIRECTLY for their nation's Commissioner and its President, or do you want your national government to keep this power, as it is now, by appointing him/her?   If the answer is to the former, then get out there and tell your country to push for a Treaty amendment and finally vote for the Executive of our Union. But, the real question is, do you really want to vote a European Commission President? Because, Brexiteers say the EU is undemocratic, and if you say ok lets democratise it by voting for the Commission, then their argument is 'Who said i want to vote for a European President'?   Therefore,Its NOT the EU's fault for the undemocratic election of the Commission, but your country's fault for not willing to amend the Treaty.   To sum up, you GOTTA decide what you want and stop MOANING!

commentText: The EU has to be the greatest, single example of an institution exuding excessive and arbitrary powers since the monarchy of the Holy Roman Empire.   The EU does not possess any of its own lands or waters. The EU is made up of territories of individual sovereign states. Yet it inexplicably interferes in the territorial affairs of those member states, a prime example being their interference in the Good Friday agreement during the Brexit negotiations.   The EU does not have any of its own money. All the money that flows through the institution is provided by the sovereign states that make up its membership. Yet it has its own currency and is responsible for the distribution of this money between those member states. The budget, which dictates this distribution, is proposed solely by the European Commission ‚Äì who are not democratically elected.   The EU does not have its own citizens. All the citizens that are under the umbrella of the EU are indeed citizens of the individual sovereign states. Yet the EU has the ultimate power to rule over these citizens through its law making and enforcement. These laws are again proposed solely by the democratically unelected European Commission.   So, what we are left with is an Institution which has no lands, no money and no citizens. Yet this institution demands an arbitrary hand in every single element of the aforementioned issues involving its member states.   The EU acts in a manner befitting that of a nation state but lacks the basic components upon which a nation state is founded.   The EU is (questionably) good only for that which the UK initially joined it for; a trading organisation, and its powers should not exceed those which a trading organisation retains.   History has proven time and time again that the implementation of arbitrary and/or unreasonable governance is almost inevitably followed by conflict. The European Union has grossly exceeded both its intended and reasonable powers and as such threatens to endanger the very peace it originally sought to preserve across the continent.  üá¨üáß

commentText: Of course the EP want to have the power to appoint the EC-President,... but for me it is OK when the European Council takes the lead in this.  There is no treaty stating that the EP should do this,.. and that is on purpose..!! If the collective governments of the member states appointed the President, this president is merely the head of the European bureaucracy, but if the EP appoints the President, the President gets a kind of autonomous democratic legitimacy ... and the whole European project takes a step towards a federation.  But that is something we have to discuss properly in Europe before we take such a step...!  I don't like those crocodile tears from the MEPs, about it not being democratic. It would be undemocratic to move towards a federation without explicit consent of the member states and their population.... The Brexit party, and the like, are hypocrites... yelling the EU to be "undemocratic", while it were those people who opposed the idea of giving the EP this power. in the first place....!
